DATA CLOUD
Billing Considerations for Data Graphs

Using data graphs impacts the consumption of credits used for billing orgs with Data Cloud licenses. For Data Cloud orgs, data graphs use batch data transforms and accelerated queries and consume space in your allocated data storage. For Customer Data Platform orgs, data graphs use space in your allocated data storage and count toward your aggregate daily limit on queries.

TYPE	DESCRIPTION
Batch data pipeline	

A data graph leverages batch data transforms to combine the source data model objects (DMOs) and build the serialized JSON blobs.

If you have a Data Cloud license, usage is calculated based on the number of rows processed by the batch data transform each time the data graph is created or refreshed.

If you have a Customer Data Platform license, there’s no billing impact when building and refreshing a data graph.


Accelerated data queries	

Usage is calculated based on the records processed.

If you have a Data Cloud license, all data graph queries are considered accelerated data queries.

If you have a Customer Data Platform license, there is no billing impact from queries against data graphs. However, the aggregate daily limit on queries applies to all queries, including data graph queries.


Storage beyond allocation	

Usage is calculated based on the amount of storage used above the amount allocated.


Related objects	

Usage is calculated based on the number of records processed.

On day one, the total number of rows in the object is considered for billing. For subsequent days, Data Cloud considers the number of active rows in the related object as records processed for billing.

For more information on how Data Cloud usage is billed, refer to your contract or contact your account executive.
